# Ollanta Humala

## Introduction: The Man Who Almost Wasn't

Ollanta Moisés Humala Tasso—yes, that’s his full name, and no, it’s not a [Peruvian](/Peru) telenova character—is a former [Peruvian](/Peru) military officer turned politician who served as the [President of Peru](/President_of_Peru) from 2011 to 2016. If you’re thinking, “Wait, wasn’t there another Humala in politics?”—yes, his brother [Antauro Humala](/Antauro_Humala) also dabbled in the family business of causing political headaches. Ollanta’s journey from a failed military uprising to the presidential palace is the kind of story that makes you question whether [Peruvian politics](/Politics_of_Peru) is a drama or a dark comedy.

Born on June 27, 1962, in [Lima](/Lima), Humala grew up in a family steeped in [ethnocacerist](/Ethnocacerism) ideology—a mix of [Indigenism](/Indigenism), [anti-imperialism](/Anti-imperialism), and a dash of “let’s overthrow the government” for flavor. His father, [Isaac Humala](/Isaac_Humala), was a lawyer and political theorist who apparently thought the best way to raise children was to indoctrinate them into his personal brand of [nationalism](/Nationalism). Spoiler: It worked.

Humala’s political career is a masterclass in reinvention. He went from leading a failed military coup in 2000 (more on that later) to running for president in 2006, losing to [Alan García](/Alan_García), and then somehow convincing Peruvians to give him another shot in 2011. His presidency was a rollercoaster of broken promises, economic stability, and enough corruption scandals to make a [telenovela](/Telenovela) writer jealous.

## Early Life and Military Career: The Making of a Rebel

### Family and Ideological Upbringing

Ollanta Humala wasn’t born in a vacuum—though sometimes it feels like his political ideas were. His father, Isaac Humala, was a devout follower of [ethnocacerism](/Ethnocacerism), a political movement that blends [Indigenous rights](/Indigenous_rights) with a healthy dose of [anti-colonialism](/Anti-colonialism) and a side of military junta nostalgia. Isaac named his sons after [Inca emperors](/Inca_Empire)—because why not?—with Ollanta being named after [Ollantay](/Ollantay), a legendary Inca general. Subtle.

The Humala siblings were raised in a household where dinner table conversations probably involved debates about [revolutionary tactics](/Revolution) rather than homework. Ollanta’s brother, Antauro, would later become infamous for leading the [Andahuaylas uprising](/Andahuaylas_uprising) in 2005, because nothing says “family bonding” like attempting to overthrow the government together.

### Military Education and Early Career

Humala followed the family tradition and joined the [Peruvian Army](/Peruvian_Army), because what else do you do when your dad’s life philosophy is “the government is corrupt and must be destroyed”? He graduated from the [Chorrillos Military School](/Chorrillos_Military_School) in 1982, just in time to witness Peru’s descent into chaos during the [internal conflict](/Internal_conflict_in_Peru) with the [Shining Path](/Shining_Path) and the [Túpac Amaru Revolutionary Movement (MRTA)](/Túpac_Amaru_Revolutionary_Movement).

Humala’s military career was, well, eventful. He served in the [Peruvian Army’s Special Forces](/Peruvian_Army#Special_Forces) and was deployed to combat zones, where he presumably learned that [guerrilla warfare](/Guerrilla_warfare) is messy and [politics](/Politics) is messier. By the late 1990s, he was a lieutenant colonel, which is impressive until you realize he’d later use that rank to try and stage a coup.

### The 2000 Coup Attempt: A Humala Family Tradition

In October 2000, Humala and a group of military officers decided that [President Alberto Fujimori](/Alberto_Fujimori)’s government had overstayed its welcome. They launched a failed uprising in [Locumba](/Locumba), a small town near the [Chilean border](/Chile–Peru_relations), because apparently, no one told them that coups are harder to pull off than they look in movies.

The rebellion was crushed faster than a [Peruvian ceviche](/Ceviche) at a lunch buffet, and Humala fled to [Venezuela](/Venezuela), where he was granted asylum by [Hugo Chávez](/Hugo_Chávez). Because of course he was. Chávez loved collecting disgruntled military officers like they were [Pokémon](/Pokémon).

Humala’s exile lasted until 2001, when Fujimori’s government collapsed under the weight of its own [corruption scandals](/Vladivideos). He returned to Peru, where he was briefly imprisoned before being released due to lack of evidence. Because in Peru, “lack of evidence” is apparently a get-out-of-jail-free card.

## Political Rise: From Coup Leader to Presidential Candidate

### The 2006 Presidential Campaign: Almost There

Humala’s first presidential run in 2006 was a wild ride. He positioned himself as a [left-wing](/Left-wing_politics) nationalist, which in Peru basically means “I’m not Fujimori, but also not a [neoliberal](/Neoliberalism).” His campaign was a mix of [anti-establishment rhetoric](/Anti-establishment) and promises to redistribute wealth, which sounded great to the [Peruvian poor](/Poverty_in_Peru) and terrifying to the [Lima elite](/Lima).

He made it to the runoff against [Alan García](/Alan_García), a former president with a reputation for [economic mismanagement](/Peruvian_economic_crisis) and a face that screamed “I’ve seen things.” García won, but Humala’s strong showing proved that Peruvians were tired of the same old [political dynasties](/Political_dynasty).

### The 2011 Presidential Campaign: Second Time’s the Charm

By 2011, Humala had done a political 180. He ditched the radical leftist image, swapped his [Che Guevara](/Che_Guevara) t-shirts for suits, and rebranded himself as a [social democrat](/Social_democracy). His new slogan? “La Gran Transformación” (“The Great Transformation”), which sounded ambitious until you realized it mostly involved not scaring off [foreign investors](/Foreign_direct_investment).

His main opponent was [Keiko Fujimori](/Keiko_Fujimori), daughter of the aforementioned [Alberto Fujimori](/Alberto_Fujimori), who was running on a platform of “my dad wasn’t that bad, honestly.” The runoff was a battle between Peru’s traumatic past and its uncertain future. Humala won by a razor-thin margin—51.4% to 48.6%—because nothing says “democratic mandate” like a 3% lead.

## Presidency (2011–2016): The Good, the Bad, and the Corrupt

### Economic Policies: Stability at What Cost?

Humala’s presidency was, economically speaking, a mixed bag. Peru’s economy grew at an average of 5.9% annually during his term, thanks largely to high [commodity prices](/Commodity) and continued [foreign investment](/Foreign_direct_investment). He expanded social programs like [Juntos](/Juntos_(Peru)) and [Pension 65](/Pension_65), which helped reduce [poverty rates](/Poverty_in_Peru).

But here’s the catch: Humala’s economic policies were basically [neoliberalism](/Neoliberalism) with a leftist veneer. He promised to renegotiate [free trade agreements](/Free_trade_agreement) but ended up keeping them. He vowed to tax [mining companies](/Mining_in_Peru) more but settled for voluntary contributions. It was like ordering a [Peruvian lomo saltado](/Lomo_saltado) and getting a [McDonald’s burger](/McDonald's) instead.

### Social and Environmental Policies: Promises, Promises

Humala’s government talked a big game about [indigenous rights](/Indigenous_rights_in_Peru) and [environmental protection](/Environmental_issues_in_Peru). In reality? Not so much. His administration approved controversial [mining projects](/Mining_in_Peru) like [Conga](/Conga_mine) and [Tía María](/Tía_María_mine), which led to massive protests and [environmental conflicts](/Environmental_conflict).

He also signed the [Prior Consultation Law](/Prior_Consultation_Law_(Peru)), which was supposed to give [indigenous communities](/Indigenous_peoples_of_Peru) a say in projects affecting their lands. Spoiler: It didn’t work as planned, because [bureaucracy](/Bureaucracy) and [corruption](/Corruption_in_Peru) have a way of ruining everything.

### Foreign Policy: Playing Both Sides

Humala’s foreign policy was a masterclass in [diplomatic ambiguity](/Diplomacy). He maintained good relations with the [United States](/United_States) while cozying up to [Venezuela](/Venezuela) and [Bolivia](/Bolivia). He supported [regional integration](/Latin_American_integration) but didn’t push too hard for it. It was like trying to be friends with both the [popular kids](/Social_hierarchy) and the [rebels](/Counterculture) in high school.

His government also played a key role in the [Peru–Chile maritime dispute](/Peru–Chile_maritime_dispute), which Peru won in 2014. Because nothing says “national pride” like a [legal victory](/International_Court_of_Justice) over your neighbor.

### Corruption Scandals: The Gift That Keeps on Giving

Ah, corruption. The one thing you can always count on in [Peruvian politics](/Corruption_in_Peru). Humala’s presidency was no exception. His government was plagued by scandals, including:

- **The Odebrecht Scandal**: [Odebrecht](/Odebrecht), the Brazilian construction giant, admitted to paying [bribes](/Bribery) to Peruvian officials, including Humala’s 2011 campaign. Because nothing says “democracy” like a [Brazilian corporation](/Corruption_in_Brazil) buying your election.

- **The Nadine Heredia Case**: Humala’s wife, [Nadine Heredia](/Nadine_Heredia), was accused of [money laundering](/Money_laundering) and [illegal campaign financing](/Campaign_finance). She was later sentenced to prison, because in Peru, even the [First Lady](/First_Lady) isn’t above the law (sometimes).

- **The “Cocktail” Scandal**: Allegations that Humala’s government received illegal donations from [Venezuelan oil money](/Petróleos_de_Venezuela). Because why not add [international intrigue](/International_relations) to the mix?

Humala and Heredia were eventually sentenced to 18 months in [preventive detention](/Preventive_detention) in 2017, because in Peru, justice moves at the speed of a [Lima traffic jam](/Traffic_in_Lima).

## Post-Presidency: From Palace to Prison

### Legal Troubles: The Fall of the Humalas

After leaving office, Humala’s legal troubles piled up faster than [Peruvian bureaucracy](/Bureaucracy_in_Peru). In 2017, he and Heredia were arrested on charges of [money laundering](/Money_laundering) and [obstruction of justice](/Obstruction_of_justice). They spent 9 months in [pre-trial detention](/Pre-trial_detention) before being released under [house arrest](/House_arrest).

In 2018, a Peruvian court sentenced them to **18 months in prison** for [obstruction of justice](/Obstruction_of_justice), because apparently, deleting emails and hiding financial records is frowned upon. Who knew?

### Political Legacy: What’s Left?

Humala’s presidency is a study in [unfulfilled potential](/Political_disillusionment). He came to power promising change but ended up governing like a [centrist](/Centrist) who couldn’t decide whether to please the [left](/Left-wing_politics) or the [right](/Right-wing_politics). His economic policies kept Peru stable, but his social and environmental promises fell flat.

His legacy is also tarnished by [corruption](/Corruption_in_Peru), which, let’s be honest, is the one thing every Peruvian president seems to have in common. Whether he was directly involved or just turned a blind eye, the scandals of his administration left a stain that’s hard to wash off.

## Cultural and Social Impact: The Humala Effect

### Public Perception: From Hero to Zero

In 2011, Humala was the [anti-establishment](/Anti-establishment) candidate who promised to shake up [Peruvian politics](/Politics_of_Peru). By 2016, he was just another politician who had failed to deliver. His approval ratings tanked faster than a [Peruvian submarine](/Peruvian_Navy), and by the end of his term, he was one of the most unpopular presidents in recent history.

### Media and Pop Culture: The Humala Brand

Humala’s presidency inspired countless [memes](/Internet_meme), [satirical news segments](/Political_satire), and even a few [documentaries](/Documentary_film). His transformation from [military rebel](/Military_coup) to [suit-wearing politician](/Politician) was a goldmine for [Peruvian comedians](/Comedy_in_Peru).

His brother, Antauro, remained a [media sensation](/Celebrity), because nothing says “family values” like one brother in prison and the other leading an armed uprising.

## Modern Relevance: Where Is He Now?

As of 2024, Humala is still dealing with the legal fallout of his presidency. He and Heredia are free but facing ongoing investigations. His political career is effectively over, though he occasionally pops up in the news to remind Peruvians that he still exists.

His presidency serves as a cautionary tale about the dangers of [populism](/Populism) and the limits of [political reinvention](/Political_rebranding). Peru has moved on, but the scars of his administration—both political and legal—remain.

## Conclusion: The Humala Paradox

Ollanta Humala’s life is a [Peruvian tragedy](/Tragedy) wrapped in a [political farce](/Farce). He went from leading a failed coup to becoming president, only to leave office under a cloud of [corruption](/Corruption) and [broken promises](/Political_broken_promises). His story is a reminder that in [Peruvian politics](/Politics_of_Peru), the line between [revolutionary](/Revolutionary) and [opportunist](/Opportunism) is thinner than a [Lima fog](/Lima_climate).

Was he a victim of a [corrupt system](/Systemic_corruption), or did he just play the game better than most? Probably both. His presidency didn’t transform Peru, but it did leave behind a legacy of [disillusionment](/Political_disillusionment) and a few good [memes](/Internet_meme).

In the end, Ollanta Humala is a footnote in [Peruvian history](/History_of_Peru)—a man who could have been a [hero](/Hero) but settled for being a [politician](/Politician). And in Peru, that’s practically the same thing.